{{italic title}} '''''BLA BLA''''' is an [[interactive film|interactive animated film]] for computer created by {{Interlanguage link multi|Vincent Morisset|fr}} with Montreal studio AATOAA, and produced by the [[National Film Board of Canada]].<ref name=Deglise>{{cite news|last=Deglise|first=Fabien|title=Bla Bla: ce film dont vous êtes le héros|url=https://www.ledevoir.com/opinion/blogues/les-mutations-tranquilles/324000/bla-bla-ce-film-dont-vous-etes-le-heros|accessdate=8 June 2011|newspaper=[[Le Devoir]]|date=25 May 2011|location=Montreal|language=French}}</ref> The online work has been described as exploring "the principles of human communication," and follows Morisset's collaborations with [[Arcade Fire]] on ''[[Neon Bible]]'', considered the first interactive music video.<ref name=Griffin>{{cite news|last=Griffin|first=John|title=Montreal artist Vincene (sic) Morisset creates interactive computer film|url=http://www2.canada.com/nanaimodailynews/news/entertainment/story.html?id=c040b907-df5b-4a90-9d42-f3e9b764b22b|accessdate=8 June 2011|newspaper=Daily News|date=30 May 2011|agency=[[Postmedia]]|location=Nanaimo}}</ref><ref name=Dixon>{{cite news|last=Dixon|first=Guy|title=Bla Bla: An Arcade Fire collaborator gets into baby talk|url=http://m.theglobeandmail.com/news/arts/movies/bla-bla-an-arcade-fire-collaborator-gets-into-baby-talk/article2106699/?service=mobile|accessdate=27 October 2011|newspaper=[[The Globe and Mail]]|date=22 July 2011}}</ref>
{{Infobox film | name = Bla Bla | image = | alt = | caption = | film name = <!-- {{Infobox name module|language|title}} or {{Infobox name module|title}} --> | director = Vincent Morisset | producer = [[Hugues Sweeney]] | writer = | screenplay = | story = | based on = <!-- {{Based on|title of the original work|creator of the original work|additional creator(s), if necessary}} --> | starring = | narrator = | music = [[Philippe Lambert]] | cinematography = | editing = | studio = | distributor = [[National Film Board of Canada]] | released = <!-- {{Film date|df=yes/no|year|month|day|location}} --> | runtime = | country = [[Canada]] | language = English | budget = | gross = }}
The characters in ''BLA BLA'' were designed by Caroline Robert using [[stop-motion]] [[puppetry]] and [[traditional animation]] as well as [[computer animation]] methods such as [[ActionScript]] [[animation]] and real-time 3D mapping. The work is designed to be principally [[non-linear]], with users constructing the story through [[point-and-click]] choices.<ref name=Dixon/><ref name=Gevaudan>{{cite news|last=Gevaudan|first=Camille|title="BLa Bla", sujet et verbe à la fois|url=http://www.liberation.fr/medias/01012341348-bla-bla-sujet-et-verbe-a-la-fois|accessdate=8 June 2011|newspaper=[[Libération]]|date=4 June 2011|location=Paris|language=French}}</ref><ref name=cr>{{cite news|last=Mark|first=Sinclair|title=BLA BLA: a film for computer|url=http://www.creativereview.co.uk/cr-blog/2011/may/bla-bla-vincent-morisset-national-film-board-canada|accessdate=9 June 2011|newspaper=[[Creative Review]]|date=17 May 2011|location=London}}</ref>
The music by composer [[Philippe Lambert]] and characters' speech was broken into short clips and distributed randomly throughout the programming, which was created by Édouard Lanctôt-Benoit. As an added bonus, ''BLA BLA'' users can also access classic NFB animated films, including works by [[Ryan Larkin]], [[René Jodoin]], [[Michèle Cournoyer]] and [[Norman McLaren]]. ''BLA BLA'' was produced for the NFB by [[Hugues Sweeney]].<ref name=Dixon/><ref name=cr/>
The work stands apart in its emphasis on achieving an emotional response in the viewer/actor. "I wanted to create moods and generate emotions through an interactive piece," Morriset says. "It's quite hard to do dramatic crescendos on a website… I thought it would be an interesting challenge." <ref>Amid Amidi (11 April 2011). [https://www.cartoonbrew.com/shorts/bla-bla-an-interactive-short-by-vincent-morisset-52296.html “Bla Bla”, An Interactive Short by Vincent Morisset.][[Cartoon Brew.]] Retrieved 23 March 2018.</ref>
''BLA BLA'' was featured in spring 2012 at a month-long live interactive presentation in Paris.<ref name="VarietyJune4">{{cite news | url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118054435?refCatId=19 | title=NFB pushes Canadian artists in edgy direction | work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | date=June 4, 2012 | accessdate=June 5, 2012 | author=Blair, Iain}}</ref>
==Awards== In March 2012, ''BLA BLA'' received the [[South by Southwest|SXSW Interactive]] Art Award as well as the Entertainment Award in the [[Communication Arts (magazine)|Communication Arts Interactive Competition]].<ref name=sxsw>{{cite news|title=SXSW prize for interactive art goes to NFB filmmaker|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/story/2012/03/15/sxsw-prize-nfb.html|accessdate=19 March 2012|newspaper=[[CBC News]]|date=15 March 2012|agency=[[Canadian Press]]}}</ref> In May 2012, it received the [[Webby Award]] for best web art.<ref name="webby">{{cite web | url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/technology/story/2012/05/01/webby-awards-canadian-winners.html | title=Webby awards honour NFB, girls say video | work=[[CBC News]] | date=May 1, 2012 | accessdate=May 12, 2012}}</ref>
